article.headline: Walker has 19 in second half for Dallas
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- Halfway through the season, the Dallas Mavericks finally seem to be getting into a groove -- a familiar one. Fueled by their outside shooting, the Mavericks beat the New Jersey Nets 106-93 Tuesday night, increasing their longest winning streak of the season to five straight. Although Dallas players were mostly proud of how they defended New Jersey's transition game, offense was the main reason the Mavericks went ahead for good late in the first quarter. Dirk Nowitzki got things going by scoring 15 of his 19 points in the first half. He hit two 3-pointers during an 18-6 run that put the Mavs up by 15; the Nets would never get closer than seven after that. Steve Nash and Michael Finley also hit 3s during that spurt and finished with 18 points each. Antoine Walker led Dallas with 22 points, 19 coming in the second half while Nowitzki was slowed by a sprained left thumb sustained after getting whacked by Kenyon Martin. "They have so many weapons," said New Jersey's Jason Kidd, who had 12 assists but shot just 4-of-11 for 10 points. "Sometimes, you just can't stop it." Martin did his best to keep pace, scoring a season-high 29 points and grabbing nine rebounds in his lone annual appearance in his hometown. Richard Jefferson added 21 points and seven rebounds. "We left too many guys wide open," Martin said. "When they're hitting like that, it's going to be a tough night. You're not going to outscore them." The Nets certainly can't. Their seven-game losing skid to Dallas is their longest against any team right now. They've also lost three straight and four of five, not exactly the way they want to be playing heading into an appearance in San Antonio on Wednesday night for a rematch of last season's finals. The Mavericks, meanwhile, are playing the way they hoped when they made offseason deals for Walker and Antawn Jamison. They're scoring a lot and winning in bunches; the five straight give them 25 at the midpoint, putting them on pace for a third straight 50-win season. "We know we can get a lot better," said Nowitzki, who also had 10 rebounds and tied his season high with six assists. "We're taking steps in the right direction. But if we want to do something in the playoffs, we've got a lot further to go." Coming off their first two-day stretch without a game in nearly three weeks, the Mavericks went ahead for good with 2:08 left in the first quarter. New Jersey got within eight in the third quarter and seven in the fourth. It was 98-90 after a breakaway dunk by Kerry Kittles with 3:40 left, then Dallas scored four straight to seal it, the capper coming on a layup by Walker with 1:51 to go. The fact the Mavs protected their big, early lead was significant considering they wasted advantages of 20 and 15 before pulling out overtime victories last week. Those games started the current winning streak.

Game notes
The teams set an NBA record by combining for only 11 turnovers, with Dallas having four and New Jersey committing seven. The Mavs also set a franchise record with no turnovers in the first half. ... The previous record for fewest combined turnovers was 12, set by Cleveland and Boston -- six each -- on March 7, 1993. ... Mavs marketers pulled off another new one, giving away 5,000 marionettes of Nowitzki. Fans will soon get to pull the strings on Nash and Finley. ... Eddie Griffin, on New Jersey's injured list, was convicted Tuesday of marijuana possession. He'll be sentenced Feb. 13. He's also facing a felony charge of aggravated assault with a deadly weapon.
